# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: corrosion-science
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Cathodic protection systems protect a wide range of metallic structures in various environments.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Common applications are: steel water or fuel pipelines and steel storage tanks such as home water heaters; steel pier piles; ship and boat hulls; offshore oil platforms and onshore oil well casings; offshore wind farm foundations and metal reinforcement bars in concrete buildings and structures.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Another common application is in galvanized steel, in which a sacrificial coating of zinc on steel parts protects them from rust.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Cathodic protection can, in some cases, prevent stress corrosion cracking.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Cathodic protection was first described by Sir Humphry Davy in a series of papers presented to the Royal Society in London in 1824.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The first application was to HMS *Samarang* in 1824.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Sacrificial anodes made from iron attached to the copper sheath of the hull below the waterline dramatically reduced the corrosion rate of the copper.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] However, a side effect of cathodic protection was the increase in marine growth.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Usually, copper when corroding releases copper ions which have an anti-fouling effect.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Since excess marine growth affected the performance of the ship, the Royal Navy decided that it was better to allow the copper to corrode and have the benefit of reduced marine growth, so cathodic protection was not used further.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Davy was assisted in his experiments by his pupil Michael Faraday, who continued his research after Davy's death.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] In 1834, Faraday discovered the quantitative connection between corrosion weight loss and electric current and thus laid the foundation for the future application of cathodic protection.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Thomas Edison experimented with impressed current cathodic protection on ships in 1890, but was unsuccessful due to the lack of a suitable current source and anode materials.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] It would be 100 years after Davy's experiment before cathodic protection was used widely on oil pipelines in the United States—cathodic protection was applied to steel gas pipelines beginning in 1928 and more widely in the 1930s.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] In the application of *passive* cathodic protection, a *galvanic anode*, a piece of a more electrochemically "active" metal (more negative electrode potential), is attached to the vulnerable metal surface where it is exposed to an electrolyte.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Galvanic anodes are selected because they have a more "active" voltage than the metal of the target structure (typically steel).
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] In this environment the steel reinforcement has a passive protective layer and remains largely stable.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Galvanic systems are "constant potential" systems that aim to restore the concrete's natural protective environment by providing a high initial current to restore passivity.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] It then reverts to a lower sacrificial current, while harmful negative chloride ions migrate away from the steel and towards the positive anode.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The anodes remain reactive through their lifetime (10–20 years typically), increasing current when the resistivity decreases due to corrosion hazards such as rainfall, temperature increases, or flooding.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The reactive nature of these anodes makes them an efficient choice.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Unlike impressed current cathodic protection (ICCP) systems, steel constant polarization is not the goal, rather the restoration of the environment.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Polarization of the target structure is caused by the electron flow from the anode to the cathode, so the two metals must have a good electrically conductive contact.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The driving force for the cathodic protection current is the difference in electrode potential between the anode and the cathode.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] During the initial phase of high current, the potential of the steel surface is polarized (pushed) more negative protecting the steel which hydroxide ion generation at the steel surface and ionic migration restore the concrete environment.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Over time the galvanic anode continues to corrode, consuming the anode material until eventually it must be replaced.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Galvanic or sacrificial anodes are made in various shapes and sizes using alloys of zinc, magnesium, and aluminium.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] ASTM International publishes standards on the composition and manufacturing of galvanic anodes.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] In order for galvanic cathodic protection to work, the anode must possess a lower (that is, more negative) electrode potential than that of the cathode (the target structure to be protected).
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The table below shows a simplified galvanic series which is used to select the anode metal.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The anode must be chosen from a material that is lower on the list than the material to be protected.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] In some cases, *impressed current cathodic protection* (ICCP) systems are used.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] These consist of anodes connected to a DC power source, often a transformer-rectifier connected to AC power.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] In the absence of an AC supply, alternative power sources may be used, such as solar panels, wind power or gas powered thermoelectric generators.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Anodes for ICCP systems are available in a variety of shapes and sizes.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Common anodes are tubular and solid rod shapes or continuous ribbons of various materials.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] These include high silicon, cast iron, graphite, mixed metal oxide (MMO), platinum and niobium coated wire and other materials.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] For pipelines, anodes are arranged in groundbeds either distributed or in a deep vertical hole depending on several design and field condition factors including current distribution requirements.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Cathodic protection transformer-rectifier units are often custom manufactured and equipped with a variety of features, including remote monitoring and control, integral current interrupters and various type of electrical enclosures.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The output DC negative terminal is connected to the structure to be protected by the cathodic protection system.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The rectifier output DC positive cable is connected to the anodes.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The AC power cable is connected to the rectifier input terminals.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The output of the ICCP system should be optimized to provide enough current to provide protection to the target structure.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Some cathodic protection transformer-rectifier units are designed with taps on the transformer windings and jumper terminals to select the voltage output of the ICCP system.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Cathodic protection transformer-rectifier units for water tanks and used in other applications are made with solid state circuits to automatically adjust the operating voltage to maintain the optimum current output or structure-to-electrolyte potential.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Analog or digital meters are often installed to show the operating voltages (DC and sometimes AC) and current output.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] For shore structures and other large complex target structures, ICCP systems are often designed with multiple independent zones of anodes with separate cathodic protection transformer-rectifier circuits.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Hybrid systems use a combination of the aforementioned systems to achieve some of the benefits of both, utilizing the restorative capabilities of ICCP systems but maintaining the reactive, lower cost, and easier-to-maintain nature of a galvanic anode.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The system is made up of wired galvanic anodes in arrays typically 400 millimetres (16 in) apart, which are then initially powered for a short period to restore the concrete and to power ionic migration.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The power supply is then taken away and the anodes are simply attached to the steel as a galvanic system.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] More powered phases can be administered if needed.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Like galvanic systems, corrosion rate monitoring from polarization tests and half-cell potential mapping can be used to measure corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Polarization is not the goal for the life of the system.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] This technology is also used to protect water heaters.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The electrons sent by the imposed current anode (composed of titanium and covered with MMO) prevent the inside of the tank from rusting.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] In order to be recognized as effective, these anodes must comply with certain standards: A cathodic protection system is considered efficient when its potential reaches or exceeds the limits established by the cathodic protection criteria.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The cathode protection criteria used come from the standard NACE SP0388-2007 (formerly RP0388-2001) of the NACE National Association of Corrosion Engineers.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Hazardous product pipelines are routinely protected by a coating supplemented with cathodic protection.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] An impressed current cathodic protection system (ICCP) for a pipeline consists of a DC power source, often an AC powered transformer rectifier and an anode, or array of anodes buried in the ground (the anode groundbed).
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The DC power source would typically have a DC output of up to 50 amperes and 50 volts, but this depends on several factors, such as the size of the pipeline and coating quality.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The positive DC output terminal would be connected via cables to the anode array, while another cable would connect the negative terminal of the rectifier to the pipeline, preferably through junction boxes to allow measurements to be taken.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Anodes can be installed in a groundbed consisting of a vertical hole backfilled with conductive coke (a material that improves the performance and life of the anodes) or laid in a prepared trench, surrounded by conductive coke and backfilled.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The choice of groundbed type and size depends on the application, location and soil resistivity.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The DC cathodic protection current is then adjusted to the optimum level after conducting various tests including measurements of pipe-to-soil potentials or electrode potential.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] When designing the system, and periodically after installation, engineers will conduct a baseline measurement campaign, during which all existing active protection systems in the area will be switched off (or as many as possible) and the *native* or *natural* pipe-to-electrode potential is recorded.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] This measurement will provide clues about how the pipeline can be sectioned into electrical systems, how many anodes and rectifiers will be needed and where they should be placed.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] It is sometimes more economically viable to protect a pipeline using galvanic (sacrificial) anodes.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] This is often the case on smaller diameter pipelines of limited length.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Galvanic anodes rely on the galvanic series potentials of the metals to drive cathodic protection current from the anode to the structure being protected.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Water pipelines of various pipe materials are also provided with cathodic protection where owners determine the cost is reasonable for the expected pipeline service life extension attributed to the application of cathodic protection.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Cathodic protection on ships is often implemented by galvanic anodes attached to the hull and ICCP for larger vessels.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Since ships are regularly removed from the water for inspections and maintenance, it is a simple task to replace the galvanic anodes.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Galvanic anodes are generally shaped to reduced drag in the water and fitted flush to the hull to also try to minimize drag.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Smaller vessels, with non-metallic hulls, such as yachts, are equipped with galvanic anodes to protect areas such as outboard motors.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] As with all galvanic cathodic protection, this application relies on a solid electrical connection between the anode and the item to be protected.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] For ICCP on ships, the anodes are usually constructed of a relatively inert material such as platinized titanium.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] A DC power supply is provided within the ship and the anodes mounted on the outside of the hull.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The anode cables are introduced into the ship via a compression seal fitting and routed to the DC power source.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The negative cable from the power supply is simply attached to the hull to complete the circuit.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Ship ICCP anodes are flush-mounted, minimizing the effects of drag on the ship, and located a minimum 5 ft below the light load line in an area to avoid mechanical damage.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The current density required for protection is a function of velocity and considered when selecting the current capacity and location of anode placement on the hull.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Some ships may require specialist treatment, for example aluminium hulls with steel fixtures will create an electrochemical cell where the aluminium hull can act as a galvanic anode and corrosion is enhanced.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] In cases like this, aluminium or zinc galvanic anodes can be used to offset the potential difference between the aluminium hull and the steel fixture.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] If the steel fixtures are large, several galvanic anodes may be required, or even a small ICCP system.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Marine cathodic protection covers many areas, jetties, harbors, offshore structures.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The variety of different types of structure leads to a variety of systems to provide protection.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Galvanic anodes are favored, but ICCP can also often be used.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Because of the wide variety of structure geometry, composition, and architecture, specialized firms are often required to engineer structure-specific cathodic protection systems.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The application to concrete reinforcement is slightly different in that the anodes and reference electrodes are usually embedded in the concrete at the time of construction when the concrete is being poured.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] For ICCP, the principle is the same as any other ICCP system.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] However, in a typical atmospherically exposed concrete structure such as a bridge, there will be many more anodes distributed through the structure as opposed to an array of anodes as used on a pipeline.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] This makes for a more complicated system and usually an automatically controlled DC power source is used, possibly with an option for remote monitoring and operation.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] For buried or submerged structures, the treatment is similar to that of any other buried or submerged structure.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Galvanic systems offer the advantage of being easier to retrofit and do not need any control systems as ICCP does.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] For pipelines constructed from pre-stressed concrete cylinder pipe (PCCP), the techniques used for cathodic protection are generally as for steel pipelines except that the applied potential must be limited to prevent damage to the prestressing wire.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The steel wire in a PCCP pipeline is stressed to the point that any corrosion of the wire can result in failure.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] An additional problem is that any excessive hydrogen ions as a result of an excessively negative potential can cause hydrogen embrittlement of the wire, also resulting in failure.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The failure of too many wires will result in catastrophic failure of the PCCP.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] To implement ICCP therefore requires very careful control to ensure satisfactory protection.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] A simpler option is to use galvanic anodes, which are self-limiting and need no control.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Vessels, pipelines and tanks (including ballast tanks) which are used to store or transport liquids can also be protected from corrosion on their internal surfaces by the use of cathodic protection.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] A common application of internal cathodic protection is water storage tanks and power plant shell and tube heat exchangers.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Galvanizing generally refers to hot-dip galvanizing which is a way of coating steel with a layer of metallic zinc or tin.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Lead or antimony are often added to the molten zinc bath, and also other metals have been studied.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Galvanized coatings are quite durable in most environments because they combine the barrier properties of a coating with some of the benefits of cathodic protection.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] If the zinc coating is scratched or otherwise locally damaged and steel is exposed, the surrounding areas of zinc coating form a galvanic cell with the exposed steel and protect it from corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] This is a form of localized cathodic protection - the zinc acts as a sacrificial anode.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Galvanizing, while using the electrochemical principle of cathodic protection, is not actually cathodic but sacrificial protection.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] In the case of galvanizing, only areas very close to the zinc are protected.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Hence, a larger area of bare steel would only be protected around the edges.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Several companies market electronic devices claiming to mitigate corrosion for automobiles and trucks.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Corrosion control professionals find they do not work.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] There is no peer reviewed scientific testing and validation supporting the use of the devices.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Under section 74.01(1) (b) of the *Competition Act Canada*, no performance claims about a product or its effectiveness can be done unless it can be proven that they are based on adequate and proper tests.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The Competition Bureau Canada proceeded to investigate several companies selling electronic corrosion devices in Canada.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Some were forced to withdraw their product from the market as they could not support their claims scientifically.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Electrode potential is measured with reference electrodes.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Copper–copper sulphate electrodes are used for structures in contact with soil or fresh water.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Silver/silver chloride/seawater electrodes or pure zinc electrodes are used for seawater applications.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The methods are described in EN 13509:2003 and NACE TM0497 along with the sources of error in the voltage that appears on the display of the meter.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Interpretation of electrode potential measurements to determine the potential at the interface between the anode of the corrosion cell and the electrolyte requires training and cannot be expected to match the accuracy of measurements done in laboratory work.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] A side effect of improperly applied cathodic protection is the production of atomic hydrogen, leading to its absorption in the protected metal and subsequent hydrogen embrittlement of welds and materials with high hardness.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Under normal conditions, the atomic hydrogen will combine at the metal surface to create hydrogen gas, which cannot penetrate the metal.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Hydrogen atoms, however, are small enough to pass through the crystalline steel structure, and can lead in some cases to hydrogen embrittlement.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] This is a process of disbondment of protective coatings from the protected structure (cathode) due to the formation of hydrogen ions over the surface of the protected material (cathode).
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Disbonding can be exacerbated by an increase in alkali ions and an increase in cathodic polarization.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The degree of disbonding is also reliant on the type of coating, with some coatings affected more than others.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Cathodic protection systems should be operated so that the structure does not become excessively polarized, since this also promotes disbonding due to excessively negative potentials.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Cathodic disbonding occurs rapidly in pipelines that contain hot fluids because the process is accelerated by heat flow.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Effectiveness of cathodic protection (CP) systems on steel pipelines can be impaired by the use of solid film backed dielectric coatings such as polyethylene tapes, shrinkable pipeline sleeves, and factory applied single or multiple solid film coatings.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] This phenomenon occurs because of the high electrical resistivity of these film backings.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Protective electric current from the cathodic protection system is blocked or shielded from reaching the underlying metal by the highly resistive film backing.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Cathodic shielding was first defined in the 1980s as being a problem, and technical papers on the subject have been regularly published since then.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Cathodic shielding is referenced in a number of the standards listed below.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] In many countries, having a related CP certificate is recommended or, in some cases, mandatory for doing a CP job, from field test to design.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] There are different certification bodies and evaluation methods, but two of them are more common: AMPP certification and ISO 15257.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] AMPP cathodic protection certification has four levels: Tester, Technician, Technologist, and Specialist.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] ISO 15257 has five levels: Four levels close to the AMPP definition, plus another level for those who have made a scientific contribution.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] The main center for cathodic protection certification in France and some French language countries is CEFRACOR.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] fkks cert GmbH (owned by fkks: Fachverband Kathodischer Korrosionsschutz e.V., trans.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] German Professional Association for Cathodic Protection specialists) is an accredited certification scheme in the field of cathodic corrosion protection.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Three different bodies will provide cathodic protection certificates based on ISO 15257: APCERT, CICPND, and RINA.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Institute of Corrosion (ICorr), Corrosion Prevention Association (CPA), and TWI offer a Cathodic Protection, Training, Assessment, and Certification Scheme that evaluates the competence levels of cathodic protection personnel.
[src:corrosion-science/cathodic-protection] Moreover, AMPP is highly active and known in the Middle East.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] In the most common use of the word, this means electrochemical oxidation of a metal reacting with an oxidant such as oxygen (O2, gaseous or dissolved), or H3O+ ions ( H+, hydrated protons) present in aqueous solution.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Rusting, the formation of red-orange iron oxides, is perhaps the most familiar example of electrochemical corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] This type of corrosion typically produces oxides or salts of the original metal and results in a distinctive coloration.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Corrosion can also occur in materials other than metals, such as ceramics or polymers, although, in this context, the term *degradation* is more common.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Corrosion degrades the useful properties of materials and structures including mechanical strength, appearance, and permeability to liquids and gases.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Many structural alloys corrode merely from exposure to moisture in air, but the process can be strongly affected by exposure to certain substances.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Corrosion can be concentrated locally to form a pit or crack, or it can extend across a wide area, more or less uniformly corroding the surface.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Because corrosion is a diffusion-controlled process, it occurs on exposed surfaces.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] As a result, methods to reduce the activity of the exposed surface, such as passivation and chromate conversion, can increase a material's corrosion resistance.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] However, some corrosion mechanisms are less visible and less predictable.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The chemistry of corrosion is complex; it can be considered an electrochemical phenomenon.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] During corrosion at a particular spot on the surface of an object made of iron, oxidation takes place and that spot behaves as an anode.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Galvanic corrosion occurs when two different metals have physical or electrical contact with each other and are immersed in a common electrolyte, or when the same metal is exposed to electrolyte with different concentrations.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] In a galvanic couple, the more active metal (the anode) corrodes at an accelerated rate and the more noble metal (the cathode) corrodes at a slower rate.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] When immersed separately, each metal corrodes at its own rate.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] What type of metal(s) to use is readily determined by following the galvanic series.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] For example, zinc is often used as a sacrificial anode for steel structures.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Galvanic corrosion is of major interest to the marine industry and also anywhere water (containing salts) contacts pipes or metal structures.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Factors such as relative size of anode, types of metal, and operating conditions (temperature, humidity, salinity, etc.) affect galvanic corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The surface area ratio of the anode and cathode directly affects the corrosion rates of the materials.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Galvanic corrosion is often prevented by the use of sacrificial anodes.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] In any given environment (one standard medium is aerated, room-temperature seawater), one metal will be either more *noble* or more *active* than others, based on how strongly its ions are bound to the surface.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Two metals in electrical contact share the same electrons, so that the "tug-of-war" at each surface is analogous to competition for free electrons between the two materials.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Using the electrolyte as a host for the flow of ions in the same direction, the noble metal will take electrons from the active one.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The resulting mass flow or electric current can be measured to establish a hierarchy of materials in the medium of interest.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] This hierarchy is called a *galvanic series* and is useful in predicting and understanding corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Often, it is possible to chemically remove the products of corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] For example, phosphoric acid in the form of *naval jelly* is often applied to ferrous tools or surfaces to remove rust.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Corrosion removal should not be confused with electropolishing, which removes some layers of the underlying metal to make a smooth surface.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] For example, phosphoric acid may also be used to electropolish copper but it does this by removing copper, not the products of copper corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Some metals are more intrinsically resistant to corrosion than others (for some examples, see galvanic series).
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] There are various ways of protecting metals from corrosion (oxidation) including painting, hot-dip galvanization, cathodic protection, and combinations of these.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The materials most resistant to corrosion are those for which corrosion is thermodynamically unfavorable.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Any corrosion products of gold or platinum tend to decompose spontaneously into pure metal, which is why these elements can be found in metallic form on Earth and have long been valued.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] More common "base" metals can only be protected by more temporary means.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Some metals have naturally slow reaction kinetics, even though their corrosion is thermodynamically favorable.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] These include such metals as zinc, magnesium, and cadmium.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] While corrosion of these metals is continuous and ongoing, it happens at an acceptably slow rate.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] An extreme example is graphite, which releases large amounts of energy upon oxidation, but has such slow kinetics that it is effectively immune to electrochemical corrosion under normal conditions.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Passivation refers to the spontaneous formation of an ultrathin film of corrosion products, known as a passive film, on the metal's surface that act as a barrier to further oxidation.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The chemical composition and microstructure of a passive film are different from the underlying metal.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Typical passive film thickness on aluminium, stainless steels, and alloys is within 10 nanometers.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The passive film is different from oxide layers that are formed upon heating and are in the micrometer thickness range – the passive film recovers if removed or damaged whereas the oxide layer does not.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Passivation in natural environments such as air, water and soil at moderate pH is seen in such materials as aluminium, stainless steel, titanium, and silicon.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Passivation is primarily determined by metallurgical and environmental factors.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The effect of pH is summarized using Pourbaix diagrams, but many other factors are influential.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Some conditions that inhibit passivation include high pH for aluminium and zinc, low pH or the presence of chloride ions for stainless steel, high temperature for titanium (in which case the oxide dissolves into the metal, rather than the electrolyte) and fluoride ions for silicon.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] On the other hand, unusual conditions may result in passivation of materials that are normally unprotected, as the alkaline environment of concrete does for steel rebar.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Exposure to a liquid metal such as mercury or hot solder can often circumvent passivation mechanisms.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] These results indicate a mechanism of "electronic passivation".
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Passivation is extremely useful in mitigating corrosion damage, however even a high-quality alloy will corrode if its ability to form a passivating film is hindered.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Proper selection of the right grade of material for the specific environment is important for the long-lasting performance of this group of materials.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] If breakdown occurs in the passive film due to chemical or mechanical factors, the resulting major modes of corrosion may include pitting corrosion, crevice corrosion, and stress corrosion cracking.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Certain conditions, such as low concentrations of oxygen or high concentrations of species such as chloride which compete as anions, can interfere with a given alloy's ability to re-form a passivating film.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] In the worst case, almost all of the surface will remain protected, but tiny local fluctuations will degrade the oxide film in a few critical points.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Corrosion at these points will be greatly amplified, and can cause *corrosion pits* of several types, depending upon conditions.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] In extreme cases, the sharp tips of extremely long and narrow corrosion pits can cause stress concentration to the point that otherwise tough alloys can shatter; a thin film pierced by an invisibly small hole can hide a thumb sized pit from view.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] These problems are especially dangerous because they are difficult to detect before a part or structure fails.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Pitting remains among the most common and damaging forms of corrosion in passivated alloys, but it can be prevented by control of the alloy's environment.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Pitting results when a small hole, or cavity, forms in the metal, usually as a result of de-passivation of a small area.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] This area becomes anodic, while part of the remaining metal becomes cathodic, producing a localized galvanic reaction.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The deterioration of this small area penetrates the metal and can lead to failure.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] This form of corrosion is often difficult to detect because it is usually relatively small and may be covered and hidden by corrosion-produced compounds.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Stainless steel can pose special corrosion challenges, since its passivating behavior relies on the presence of a major alloying component (chromium, at least 11.5%).
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Because of the elevated temperatures of welding and heat treatment, chromium carbides can form in the grain boundaries of stainless alloys.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] This chemical reaction robs the material of chromium in the zone near the grain boundary, making those areas much less resistant to corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] This creates a galvanic couple with the well-protected alloy nearby, which leads to "weld decay" (corrosion of the grain boundaries in the heat affected zones) in highly corrosive environments.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] This process can seriously reduce the mechanical strength of welded joints over time.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] A stainless steel is said to be "sensitized" if chromium carbides are formed in the microstructure.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] A typical microstructure of a normalized type 304 stainless steel shows no signs of sensitization, while a heavily sensitized steel shows the presence of grain boundary precipitates.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The dark lines in the sensitized microstructure are networks of chromium carbides formed along the grain boundaries.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Special alloys, either with low carbon content or with added carbon "getters" such as titanium and niobium (in types 321 and 347, respectively), can prevent this effect, but the latter require special heat treatment after welding to prevent the similar phenomenon of "knifeline attack".
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] As its name implies, corrosion is limited to a very narrow zone adjacent to the weld, often only a few micrometers across, making it even less noticeable.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Crevice corrosion is a localized form of corrosion occurring in confined spaces (crevices), to which the access of the working fluid from the environment is limited.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Formation of a differential aeration cell leads to corrosion inside the crevices.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Examples of crevices are gaps and contact areas between parts, under gaskets or seals, inside cracks and seams, spaces filled with deposits, and under sludge piles.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Crevice corrosion is influenced by the crevice type (metal-metal, metal-non-metal), crevice geometry (size, surface finish), and metallurgical and environmental factors.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The susceptibility to crevice corrosion can be evaluated with ASTM standard procedures.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] A critical crevice corrosion temperature is commonly used to rank a material's resistance to crevice corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] In the chemical industry, hydrogen grooving is the corrosion of piping at grooves created by the interaction of a corrosive agent, corroded pipe constituents, and hydrogen gas bubbles.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] For example, when sulfuric acid (H2SO4) flows through steel pipes, the iron in the steel reacts with the acid to form a passivation coating of iron sulfate (FeSO4) and hydrogen gas (H2).
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The iron sulfate coating will protect the steel from further reaction; however, if hydrogen bubbles contact this coating, it will be removed.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Thus, a groove can be formed by a travelling bubble, exposing more steel to the acid, causing a vicious cycle.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The grooving is exacerbated by the tendency of subsequent bubbles to follow the same path.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] High-temperature corrosion is chemical deterioration of a material (typically a metal) as a result of heating.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] This non-galvanic form of corrosion can occur when a metal is subjected to a hot atmosphere containing oxygen, sulfur ("sulfidation"), or other compounds capable of oxidizing (or assisting the oxidation of) the material concerned.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] For example, materials used in aerospace, power generation, and even in car engines must resist sustained periods at high temperature, during which they may be exposed to an atmosphere containing the potentially highly-corrosive products of combustion.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Some products of high-temperature corrosion can potentially be turned to the advantage of the engineer.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The formation of oxides on stainless steels, for example, can provide a protective layer preventing further atmospheric attack, allowing for a material to be used for sustained periods at both room and high temperatures in hostile conditions.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Such high-temperature corrosion products, in the form of compacted oxide layer glazes, prevent or reduce wear during high-temperature sliding contact of metallic (or metallic and ceramic) surfaces.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Thermal oxidation is also commonly used to produce controlled oxide nanostructures, including nanowires and thin films.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Microbial corrosion, or commonly known as microbiologically influenced corrosion (MIC), is a corrosion caused or promoted by microorganisms, usually chemoautotrophs.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] It can apply to both metallic and non-metallic materials, in the presence or absence of oxygen.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Sulfate-reducing bacteria are active in the absence of oxygen (anaerobic); they produce hydrogen sulfide, causing sulfide stress cracking.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] In the presence of oxygen (aerobic), some bacteria may directly oxidize iron to iron oxides and hydroxides, other bacteria oxidize sulfur and produce sulfuric acid causing biogenic sulfide corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Concentration cells can form in the deposits of corrosion products, leading to localized corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Accelerated low-water corrosion (ALWC) is a particularly aggressive form of MIC that affects steel piles in seawater near the low water tide mark.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] It is characterized by an orange sludge, which smells of hydrogen sulfide when treated with acid.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Corrosion rates can be very high and design corrosion allowances can soon be exceeded leading to premature failure of the steel pile.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Piles that have been coated and have cathodic protection installed at the time of construction are not susceptible to ALWC.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] For unprotected piles, sacrificial anodes can be installed locally to the affected areas to inhibit the corrosion or a complete retrofitted sacrificial anode system can be installed.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Affected areas can also be treated using cathodic protection, using either sacrificial anodes or applying current to an inert anode to produce a calcareous deposit, which will help shield the metal from further attack.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Metal dusting is a catastrophic form of corrosion that occurs when susceptible materials are exposed to environments with high carbon activities, such as synthesis gas and other high-CO environments.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The corrosion manifests itself as a break-up of bulk metal to metal powder.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The suspected mechanism is firstly the deposition of a graphite layer on the surface of the metal, usually from carbon monoxide (CO) in the vapor phase.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] This graphite layer is then thought to form metastable M3C species (where M is the metal), which migrate away from the metal surface.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] However, in some regimes, no M3C species is observed indicating a direct transfer of metal atoms into the graphite layer.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Various treatments are used to slow corrosion damage to metallic objects which are exposed to the weather, salt water, acids, or other hostile environments.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Some unprotected metallic alloys are extremely vulnerable to corrosion, such as those used in neodymium magnets, which can spall or crumble into powder even in dry, temperature-stable indoor environments unless properly treated.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] When surface treatments are used to reduce corrosion, great care must be taken to ensure complete coverage, without gaps, cracks, or pinhole defects.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Small defects can act as an "Achilles' heel", allowing corrosion to penetrate the interior and causing extensive damage even while the outer protective layer remains apparently intact for a period of time.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Plating, painting, and the application of enamel are the most common anti-corrosion treatments.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] They work by providing a barrier of corrosion-resistant material between the damaging environment and the structural material.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Aside from cosmetic and manufacturing issues, there may be tradeoffs in mechanical flexibility versus resistance to abrasion and high temperature.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Platings usually fail only in small sections, but if the plating is more noble than the substrate (for example, chromium on steel), a galvanic couple will cause any exposed area to corrode much more rapidly than an unplated surface would.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] For this reason, it is often wise to plate with active metal such as zinc or cadmium.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] If the zinc coating is not thick enough the surface soon becomes unsightly with rusting obvious.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The design life is directly related to the metal coating thickness.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Painting either by roller or brush is more desirable for tight spaces; spray would be better for larger coating areas such as steel decks and waterfront applications.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Flexible polyurethane coatings, like Durabak-M26 for example, can provide an anti-corrosive seal with a highly durable slip resistant membrane.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Painted coatings are relatively easy to apply and have fast drying times although temperature and humidity may cause dry times to vary.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] If the environment is controlled (especially in recirculating systems), corrosion inhibitors can often be added to it.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] These chemicals form an electrically insulating or chemically impermeable coating on exposed metal surfaces, to suppress electrochemical reactions.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Such methods make the system less sensitive to scratches or defects in the coating, since extra inhibitors can be made available wherever metal becomes exposed.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Aluminium alloys often undergo a surface treatment.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Electrochemical conditions in the bath are carefully adjusted so that uniform pores, several nanometers wide, appear in the metal's oxide film.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] These pores allow the oxide to grow much thicker than passivating conditions would allow.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] At the end of the treatment, the pores are allowed to seal, forming a harder-than-usual surface layer.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] If this coating is scratched, normal passivation processes take over to protect the damaged area.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Anodizing is very resilient to weathering and corrosion, so it is commonly used for building facades and other areas where the surface will come into regular contact with the elements.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] While being resilient, it must be cleaned frequently.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] If left without cleaning, panel edge staining will naturally occur.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Anodization is the process of converting an anode into cathode by bringing a more active anode in contact with it.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] A new form of protection has been developed by applying certain species of bacterial films to the surface of metals in highly corrosive environments.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] This process increases the corrosion resistance substantially.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Alternatively, antimicrobial-producing biofilms can be used to inhibit mild steel corrosion from sulfate-reducing bacteria.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Controlled permeability formwork (CPF) is a method of preventing the corrosion of reinforcement by naturally enhancing the durability of the cover during concrete placement.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] CPF has been used in environments to combat the effects of carbonation, chlorides, frost, and abrasion.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Cathodic protection (CP) is a technique to control the corrosion of a metal surface by making it the cathode of an electrochemical cell.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Cathodic protection systems are most commonly used to protect steel pipelines and tanks; steel pier piles, ships, and offshore oil platforms.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] For effective CP, the potential of the steel surface is polarized (pushed) more negative until the metal surface has a uniform potential.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] With a uniform potential, the driving force for the corrosion reaction is halted.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] For galvanic CP systems, the anode material corrodes under the influence of the steel, and eventually it must be replaced.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The polarization is caused by the current flow from the anode to the cathode, driven by the difference in electrode potential between the anode and the cathode.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The most common sacrificial anode materials are aluminum, zinc, magnesium and related alloys.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Aluminum has the highest capacity, and magnesium has the highest driving voltage and is thus used where resistance is higher.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Zinc is general purpose and the basis for galvanizing.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] A number of problems are associated with sacrificial anodes.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Among these, from an environmental perspective, is the release of zinc, magnesium, aluminum and heavy metals such as cadmium into the environment including seawater.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] From a working perspective, sacrificial anodes systems are considered to be less precise than modern cathodic protection systems such as Impressed Current Cathodic Protection (ICCP) systems.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Their ability to provide requisite protection has to be checked regularly by means of underwater inspection by divers.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Furthermore, as they have a finite lifespan, sacrificial anodes need to be replaced regularly over time.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] For larger structures, galvanic anodes cannot economically deliver enough current to provide complete protection.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Impressed current cathodic protection (ICCP) systems use anodes connected to a DC power source (such as a cathodic protection rectifier).
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Anodes for ICCP systems are tubular and solid rod shapes of various specialized materials.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] These include high silicon cast iron, graphite, mixed metal oxide or platinum coated titanium or niobium coated rod and wires.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Anodic protection impresses anodic current on the structure to be protected (opposite to the cathodic protection).
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] It is appropriate for metals that exhibit passivity (e.g. stainless steel) and suitably small passive current over a wide range of potentials.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] It is used in aggressive environments, such as solutions of sulfuric acid.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The formation of an oxide layer is described by the Deal–Grove model, which is used to predict and control oxide layer formation in diverse situations.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] A simple test for measuring corrosion is the weight loss method.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The method involves exposing a clean weighed piece of the metal or alloy to the corrosive environment for a specified time followed by cleaning to remove corrosion products and weighing the piece to determine the loss of weight.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] where *k* is a constant, *W* is the weight loss of the metal in time *t*, *A* is the surface area of the metal exposed, and *ρ* is the density of the metal (in g/cm3).
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Other common expressions for the corrosion rate is penetration depth and change of mechanical properties.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] In 2002, the US Federal Highway Administration released a study titled "Corrosion Costs and Preventive Strategies in the United States" on the direct costs associated with metallic corrosion in the US industry.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] In 1998, the total annual direct cost of corrosion in the US roughly $276 billion (or 3.2% of the US gross domestic product at the time).
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Broken down into five specific industries, the economic losses are $22.6 billion in infrastructure, $17.6 billion in production and manufacturing, $29.7 billion in transportation, $20.1 billion in government, and $47.9 billion in utilities.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Rust is one of the most common causes of bridge accidents.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] As rust displaces a much higher volume than the originating mass of iron, its build-up can also cause failure by forcing apart adjacent components.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] It was the cause of the collapse of the Mianus River Bridge in 1983, when support bearings rusted internally and pushed one corner of the road slab off its support.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Three drivers on the roadway at the time died as the slab fell into the river below.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The following NTSB investigation showed that a drain in the road had been blocked for road re-surfacing, and had not been unblocked; as a result, runoff water penetrated the support hangers.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Rust was also an important factor in the Silver Bridge disaster of 1967 in West Virginia, when a steel suspension bridge collapsed within a minute, killing 46 drivers and passengers who were on the bridge at the time.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Similarly, corrosion of concrete-covered steel and iron can cause the concrete to spall, creating severe structural problems.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] It is one of the most common failure modes of reinforced concrete bridges.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Measuring instruments based on the half-cell potential can detect the potential corrosion spots before total failure of the concrete structure is reached.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Until 20–30 years ago, galvanized steel pipe was used extensively in the potable water systems for single and multi-family residents as well as commercial and public construction.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Today, these systems have long ago consumed the protective zinc and are corroding internally, resulting in poor water quality and pipe failures.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The economic impact on homeowners, condo dwellers, and the public infrastructure is estimated at $22 billion as the insurance industry braces for a wave of claims due to pipe failures.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Most ceramic materials are almost entirely immune to corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The strong chemical bonds that hold them together leave very little free chemical energy in the structure; they can be thought of as already corroded.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] When corrosion does occur, it is almost always a simple dissolution of the material or chemical reaction, rather than an electrochemical process.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] A common example of corrosion protection in ceramics is the lime added to soda–lime glass to reduce its solubility in water; though it is not nearly as soluble as pure sodium silicate, normal glass does form sub-microscopic flaws when exposed to moisture.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Due to its brittleness, such flaws cause a dramatic reduction in the strength of a glass object during its first few hours at room temperature.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Polymer degradation involves several complex and often poorly understood physiochemical processes.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] These are strikingly different from the other processes discussed here, and so the term "corrosion" is only applied to them in a loose sense of the word.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Because of their large molecular weight, very little entropy can be gained by mixing a given mass of polymer with another substance, making them generally quite difficult to dissolve.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] While dissolution is a problem in some polymer applications, it is relatively simple to design against.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] A more common and related problem is "swelling", where small molecules infiltrate the structure, reducing strength and stiffness and causing a volume change.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Conversely, many polymers (notably flexible vinyl) are intentionally swelled with plasticizers, which can be leached out of the structure, causing brittleness or other undesirable changes.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The most common form of degradation, however, is a decrease in polymer chain length.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Mechanisms which break polymer chains are familiar to biologists because of their effect on DNA: ionizing radiation (most commonly ultraviolet light), free radicals, and oxidizers such as oxygen, ozone, and chlorine.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Ozone cracking is a well-known problem affecting natural rubber for example.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Plastic additives can slow these process very effectively, and can be as simple as a UV-absorbing pigment (e.g., titanium dioxide or carbon black).
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Plastic shopping bags often do not include these additives so that they break down more easily as ultrafine particles of litter.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Glass is characterized by a high degree of corrosion resistance.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Because of its high water resistance, it is often used as primary packaging material in the pharmaceutical industry since most medicines are preserved in a watery solution.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Besides its water resistance, glass is also robust when exposed to certain chemically-aggressive liquids or gases.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Glass disease is the corrosion of silicate glasses in aqueous solutions.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] It is governed by two mechanisms: diffusion-controlled leaching (ion exchange) and hydrolytic dissolution of the glass network.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Both mechanisms strongly depend on the pH of contacting solution: the rate of ion exchange decreases with pH as 10−0.5pH, whereas the rate of hydrolytic dissolution increases with pH as 100.5pH.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The overall corrosion rate is a sum of contributions from both mechanisms (leaching + dissolution): NR*i*=NR*x**i*+NR*h*.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] Diffusion-controlled leaching (ion exchange) is characteristic of the initial phase of corrosion and involves replacement of alkali ions in the glass by a hydronium (H3O+) ion from the solution.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] It causes an ion-selective depletion of near surface layers of glasses and gives an inverse-square-root dependence of corrosion rate with exposure time.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] where *t* is time, *D**i* is the *i*th cation effective diffusion coefficient (cm2/d), which depends on pH of contacting water as *D**i* = *D**i*0·10–pH, and *ρ* is the density of the glass (g/cm3).
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] where *rh* is the stationary hydrolysis (dissolution) rate of the glass (cm/d).
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] In closed systems, the consumption of protons from the aqueous phase increases the pH and causes a fast transition to hydrolysis.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] However, a further saturation of solution with silica impedes hydrolysis and causes the glass to return to an ion-exchange; e.g., diffusion-controlled regime of corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] In typical natural conditions, normalized corrosion rates of silicate glasses are very low and are of the order of 10−7 to 10−5 g/(cm2·d).
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The very high durability of silicate glasses in water makes them suitable for hazardous and nuclear waste immobilisation.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] There exist numerous standardized procedures for measuring the corrosion (also called **chemical durability**) of glasses in neutral, basic, and acidic environments, under simulated environmental conditions, in simulated body fluid, at high temperature and pressure, and under other conditions.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The volume of HCl required for neutralization is classified according to the table below.
[src:corrosion-science/corrosion] The standardized test ISO 719 is not suitable for glasses with poor or not extractable alkaline components, but which are still attacked by water; e.g., quartz glass, B2O3 glass or P2O5 glass.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] A similar type of corrosion caused by the presence of an external electric current is called *electrolytic corrosion*.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] Dissimilar metals and alloys have different electrode potentials, and when two or more come into contact in an electrolyte, one metal (that is more reactive) acts as anode and the other (that is less reactive) as cathode.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] The electropotential difference between the reactions at the two electrodes is the driving force for an accelerated attack on the anode metal, which dissolves into the electrolyte.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] This leads to the metal at the anode corroding more quickly than it otherwise would and corrosion at the cathode being inhibited.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] The presence of an electrolyte and an electrical conducting path between the metals is essential for galvanic corrosion to occur.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] The electrolyte provides a means for ion migration whereby ions move to prevent charge build-up that would otherwise stop the reaction.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] If the electrolyte contains only metal ions that are not easily reduced (such as Na+, Ca2+, K+, Mg2+, or Zn2+), the cathode reaction is the reduction of dissolved H+ to H2 or O2 to OH−.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] In some cases, this type of reaction is intentionally encouraged.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] For example, low-cost household batteries typically contain carbon-zinc cells.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] As part of a closed circuit (the electron pathway), the zinc within the cell will corrode preferentially (the ion pathway) as an essential part of the battery producing electricity.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] Another example is the cathodic protection of buried or submerged structures as well as hot water storage tanks.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] In this case, sacrificial anodes work as part of a galvanic couple, promoting corrosion of the anode, while protecting the cathode metal.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] In other cases, such as mixed metals in piping (for example, copper, cast iron and other cast metals), galvanic corrosion will contribute to accelerated corrosion of parts of the system.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] Corrosion inhibitors such as sodium nitrite or sodium molybdate can be injected into these systems to reduce the galvanic potential.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] However, the application of these corrosion inhibitors must be monitored closely.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] If the application of corrosion inhibitors increases the conductivity of the water within the system, the galvanic corrosion potential can be greatly increased.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] Acidity or alkalinity (pH) is also a major consideration with regard to closed loop bimetallic circulating systems.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] Should the pH and corrosion inhibition doses be incorrect, galvanic corrosion will be accelerated.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] In most HVAC systems, the use of sacrificial anodes and cathodes is not an option, as they would need to be applied within the plumbing of the system and, over time, would corrode and release particles that could cause potential mechanical damage to circulating pumps, heat exchangers, etc.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] A common example of galvanic corrosion occurs in galvanized iron, a sheet of iron or steel covered with a zinc coating.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] Even when the protective zinc coating is broken, the underlying steel is not attacked.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] Instead, the zinc is corroded because it is less "noble".
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] Only after it has been consumed can rusting of the base metal occur.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] By contrast, with a conventional tin can, the opposite of a protective effect occurs: because the tin is more noble than the underlying steel, when the tin coating is broken, the steel beneath is immediately attacked preferentially.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] A spectacular example of galvanic corrosion occurred in the Statue of Liberty when regular maintenance checks in the 1980s revealed that corrosion had taken place between the outer copper skin and the wrought iron support structure.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] Although the problem had been anticipated when the structure was built by Gustave Eiffel to Frédéric Bartholdi's design in the 1880s, the insulation layer of shellac between the two metals had failed over time and resulted in rusting of the iron supports.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] An extensive renovation was carried out with replacement of the original insulation with PTFE.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] The structure was far from unsafe owing to the large number of unaffected connections, but it was regarded as a precautionary measure to preserve a national symbol of the United States.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] In 1681, Samuel Pepys (then serving as Admiralty Secretary) agreed to the removal of lead sheathing from English Royal Navy vessels to prevent the mysterious disintegration of their rudder-irons and bolt-heads, though he confessed himself baffled as to the reason the lead caused the corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] The problem recurred when vessels were sheathed in copper to reduce marine weed accumulation and protect against shipworm.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] In an experiment, the Royal Navy in 1761 had tried fitting the hull of the frigate HMS *Alarm* with 12-ounce copper plating.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] To the surprise of the inspection teams, however, some of the iron nails were virtually undamaged.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] Closer inspection revealed that water-resistant brown paper trapped under the nail head had inadvertently protected some of the nails: "Where this covering was perfect, the Iron was preserved from Injury".
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] The copper sheathing had been delivered to the dockyard wrapped in the paper which was not always removed before the sheets were nailed to the hull.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] The conclusion therefore reported to the Admiralty in 1763 was that iron should not be allowed direct contact with copper in sea water.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] Serious galvanic corrosion has been reported on the latest US Navy attack littoral combat vessel the USS *Independence* caused by steel water jet propulsion systems attached to an aluminium hull.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] Without electrical isolation between the steel and aluminium, the aluminium hull acts as an anode to the stainless steel, resulting in aggressive galvanic corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] The unexpected fall in 2011 of a heavy light fixture from the ceiling of the Big Dig vehicular tunnel in Boston revealed that corrosion had weakened its support.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] Improper use of aluminium in contact with stainless steel had caused rapid corrosion in the presence of salt water.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] The electrochemical potential difference between stainless steel and aluminium is in the range of 0.5 to 1.0 V, depending on the exact alloys involved, and can cause considerable corrosion within months under unfavorable conditions.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] Thousands of failing lights would have to be replaced, at an estimated cost of $54 million.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] A "lasagna cell" is accidentally produced when salty moist food such as lasagna or sauerkraut is stored in a steel baking pan and is covered with aluminium foil.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] After a few hours the foil develops small holes where it touches the lasagna, and the food surface becomes covered with small spots composed of corroded aluminium.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] In this example, the salty food (lasagna) is the electrolyte, the aluminium foil is the anode, and the steel pan is the cathode.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] If the aluminium foil touches the electrolyte only in small areas, the galvanic corrosion is concentrated, and corrosion can occur fairly rapidly.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] If the aluminium foil was not used with a dissimilar metal container, the reaction was probably a chemical one.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] It is possible for heavy concentrations of salt, vinegar or some other acidic compounds to cause the foil to disintegrate.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] The product of either of these reactions is an aluminium salt.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] It does not harm the food, but any deposit may impart an undesired flavor and color.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] The common technique of cleaning silverware by immersion in a hot electrolytic bath with a piece of aluminium is an example of galvanic corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] Aluminium foil is preferred because of its much greater surface area than that of ingots, although if the foil has a "non-stick" face, this must be removed with steel wool first.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] The electrolytic bath is usually composed of water and sodium bicarbonate, i.e., household baking soda.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] Silver darkens and corrodes in the presence of airborne sulfur molecules, and the copper in sterling silver corrodes under a variety of conditions.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] All metals can be classified into a galvanic series representing the electrical potential they develop in a given electrolyte against a standard reference electrode.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] The relative position of two metals on such a series gives a good indication of which metal is more likely to corrode more quickly.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] However, other factors such as water aeration and flow rate can influence the rate of the process markedly.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] The compatibility of two different metals may be predicted by consideration of their anodic index.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] This parameter is a measure of the electrochemical voltage that will be developed between the metal and gold.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] To find the relative voltage of a pair of metals it is only required to subtract their anodic indices.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] To reduce galvanic corrosion for metals stored in normal environments such as storage in warehouses or non-temperature and humidity controlled environments, there should not be more than 0.25 V difference in the anodic index of the two metals in contact.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] For controlled environments in which temperature and humidity are controlled, 0.50 V can be tolerated.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] For harsh environments such as outdoors, high humidity, and salty environments, there should be not more than 0.15 V difference in the anodic index.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] For example: gold and silver have a difference of 0.15 V, therefore the two metals will not experience significant corrosion even in a harsh environment.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] When design considerations require that dissimilar metals come in contact, the difference in anodic index is often managed by finishes and plating.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] The finishing and plating selected allow the dissimilar materials to be in contact, while protecting the more base materials from corrosion by the more noble.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] It will always be the metal with the most negative anodic index which will ultimately suffer from corrosion when galvanic incompatibility is in play.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] This is why sterling silver and stainless steel tableware should never be placed together in a dishwasher at the same time, as the steel items will likely experience corrosion by the end of the cycle (soap and water having served as the chemical electrolyte, and heat having accelerated the process).
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] The term "electrolytic corrosion" is most frequently used to indicate corrosion caused by electric current applied to the metal from external sources.
[src:corrosion-science/galvanic-corrosion] The mechanism of this corrosion is essentially the same as for the galvanic corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] When exposed to air, many metals naturally form a hard, relatively inert surface layer, usually an oxide (termed the "native oxide layer") or a nitride, that serves as a passivation layer.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] In the case of silver, the dark tarnish is a passivation layer of silver sulfide formed from reaction with environmental hydrogen sulfide.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] The inert surface layer formed by reaction with air has a thickness of about 1.5 nm for silicon, 1–10 nm for beryllium, and 1 nm initially for titanium, growing to 25 nm after several years.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Similarly, for aluminium, it grows to about 5 nm after several years.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Surface passivation of silicon usually consists of high-temperature thermal oxidation.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] There has been much interest in determining the mechanisms that govern the increase of thickness of the oxide layer over time.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Some of the important factors are the volume of oxide relative to the volume of the parent metal, the mechanism of oxygen diffusion through the metal oxide to the parent metal, and the relative chemical potential of the oxide.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Boundaries between micro grains, if the oxide layer is crystalline, form an important pathway for oxygen to reach the unoxidized metal below.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] For this reason, vitreous oxide coatings – which lack grain boundaries – can retard oxidation.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] The conditions necessary, but not sufficient, for passivation are recorded in Pourbaix diagrams.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Some corrosion inhibitors help the formation of a passivation layer on the surface of the metals to which they are applied.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Some compounds, dissolved in solutions (chromates, molybdates) form non-reactive and low solubility films on metal surfaces.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] In the mid 1800s, Christian Friedrich Schönbein discovered that when a piece of iron is placed in dilute nitric acid, it will dissolve and produce hydrogen, but if the iron is placed in concentrated nitric acid and then returned to the dilute nitric acid, little or no reaction will take place.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Schönbein named the first state the active condition and the second the passive condition.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] If passive iron is touched by active iron, it becomes active again.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Lillie measured the effect of an active piece of iron touching a passive iron wire and found that "a wave of activation sweeps rapidly (at some hundred centimeters a second) over its whole length".
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Aluminium naturally forms a thin surface layer of aluminium oxide on contact with oxygen in the atmosphere through a process called oxidation, which creates a physical barrier to corrosion or further oxidation in many environments.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Some aluminium alloys, however, do not form the oxide layer well, and thus are not protected against corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] There are methods to enhance the formation of the oxide layer for certain alloys.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] For example, prior to storing hydrogen peroxide in an aluminium container, the container can be passivated by rinsing it with a dilute solution of nitric acid and peroxide alternating with deionized water.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] The nitric acid and peroxide mixture oxidizes and dissolves any impurities on the inner surface of the container, and the deionized water rinses away the acid and oxidized impurities.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Generally, there are two main ways to passivate aluminium alloys (not counting plating, painting, and other barrier coatings): chromate conversion coating and anodizing.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Alclading, which metallurgically bonds thin layers of pure aluminium or alloy to different base aluminium alloy, is not strictly passivation of the *base* alloy.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] However, the aluminium layer clad on is designed to spontaneously develop the oxide layer and thus protect the base alloy.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Chromate conversion coating converts the surface aluminium to an aluminium chromate coating in the range of 0.00001–0.00004 inches (250–1,000 nm) in thickness.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Aluminium chromate conversion coatings are amorphous in structure with a gel-like composition hydrated with water.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Chromate conversion is a common way of passivating not only aluminium, but also zinc, cadmium, copper, silver, magnesium, and tin alloys.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Anodizing is an electrolytic process that forms a thicker oxide layer.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] The anodic coating consists of hydrated aluminium oxide and is considered resistant to corrosion and abrasion.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] This finish is more robust than the other processes and also provides electrical insulation, which the other two processes may not.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Because of its widespread use, iron has attracted much attention.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Rust is an example of a non-adherent oxide coating that is not passivating.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Ferrous materials, including steel, may be somewhat protected by promoting oxidation ("rust") and then converting the oxidation to a metalophosphate by using phosphoric acid and add further protection by surface coating.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] As the uncoated surface is water-soluble, a preferred method is to form manganese or zinc compounds by a process commonly known as parkerizing or phosphate conversion.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Older, less-effective but chemically-similar electrochemical conversion coatings included black oxidizing, historically known as bluing or browning.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Ordinary steel forms a passivating layer in alkali environments, as reinforcing bar does in concrete.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Stainless steels are corrosion-resistant, but they are not completely impervious to rusting.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] One common mode of corrosion in corrosion-resistant steels is when small spots on the surface begin to rust because grain boundaries or embedded bits of foreign matter (such as grinding swarf) allow water molecules to oxidize some of the iron in those spots despite the alloying chromium.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Some grades of stainless steel are especially resistant to rouging; parts made from them may therefore forgo any passivation step, depending on engineering decisions.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] While nitric acid is commonly used as a passivating acid for stainless steel, citric acid is gaining in popularity as it is far less dangerous to handle, less toxic, and biodegradable, making disposal less of a challenge.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Passivating temperatures can range from ambient to 60 degrees C, or 140 degrees F, while minimum passivation times are usually 20 to 30 minutes.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] After passivation, the parts are neutralized using a bath of aqueous sodium hydroxide, then rinsed with clean water and dried.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] The passive surface is validated using humidity, elevated temperature, a rusting agent (salt spray), or some combination of the three.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] The passivation process removes exogenous iron, creates/restores a passive oxide layer that prevents further oxidation (rust), and cleans the parts of dirt, scale, or other welding-generated compounds (e.g. oxides).
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Passivation processes are generally controlled by industry standards, the most prevalent among them today being ASTM A 967 and AMS 2700.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] These industry standards generally list several passivation processes that can be used, with the choice of specific method left to the customer and vendor.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] The "method" is either a nitric acid-based passivating bath, or a citric acid-based bath, these acids remove surface iron and rust, while sparing the chromium.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] The various 'types' listed under each method refer to differences in acid bath temperature and concentration.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Sodium dichromate is often required as an additive to oxidise the chromium in certain 'types' of nitric-based acid baths, however this chemical is highly toxic.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] With citric acid, simply rinsing and drying the part and allowing the air to oxidise it, or in some cases the application of other chemicals, is used to perform the passivation of the surface.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] It is not uncommon for some aerospace manufacturers to have additional guidelines and regulations when passivating their products that exceed the national standard.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Often, these requirements will be cascaded down using Nadcap or some other accreditation system.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Various testing methods are available to determine the passivation (or passive state) of stainless steel.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] The most common methods for validating the passivity of a part is some combination of high humidity and heat for a period of time, intended to induce rusting.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Electro-chemical testers can also be utilized to commercially verify passivation.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] The surface of titanium and of titanium-rich alloys oxidizes immediately upon exposure to air to form a thin passivation layer of titanium oxide, mostly titanium dioxide.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] This layer makes it resistant to further corrosion, aside from gradual growth of the oxide layer, thickening to ~25 nm after several years in air.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] This protective layer makes it suitable for use even in corrosive environments such as sea water.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Titanium can be anodized to produce a thicker passivation layer.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] As with many other metals, this layer causes thin-film interference which makes the metal surface appear colored, with the thickness of the passivation layer directly effecting the color produced.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Nickel can be used for handling elemental fluorine, owing to the formation of a passivation layer of nickel fluoride.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] This fact is useful in water treatment and sewage treatment applications.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] In the area of microelectronics and photovoltaic solar cells, surface passivation is usually implemented by thermal oxidation at about 1000 °C to form a coating of silicon dioxide.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Surface passivation is critical to solar cell efficiency.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] The effect of passivation on the efficiency of ranges from 3-7%.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] The surface resistivity is high, >100 Ωcm.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Passivation almost always refers to coatings on metals, usually oxides.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] Passivation can however be applied to a broad class of materials beyond metals.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] The metal-organic compounds called perovskite solar cells can be protected using passivating coatings that also improves the photoelectric conversion efficiency.
[src:corrosion-science/passivation-chemistry] In carbon quantum dot (CQD) technology, passivation has also been explored.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] The evolution of the pit density (number of pits per surface area) as a function of time follows a sigmoid curve with the characteristic shape of a logistic function curve, or a hyperbolic tangent.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] (2018), after a statistical analysis of hundreds of individual pits observed on carbon steel surfaces at the nano-to-micro- scales, distinguish three stages of pitting corrosion: induction, propagation, and saturation.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] The pit formation can be essentially regarded as a two step process: nucleation followed by a growth.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] The process of pit nucleation is initiated by the depassivation of the protective oxide layer isolating the metal substrate from the aggressive solution.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] The depassivation of the protective oxide layer is the less properly understood step in pitting corrosion and its very local and random appearance probably its most enigmatic characteristic.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Mechanical or physical damages may locally disrupt the protective layer.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Crystalline defects, or impurity inclusions, pre-existing in the base metal material can also serve as nucleation points (especially metal sulfide inclusions).
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] The chemical conditions prevailing in the solution and the nature of the metal, or the alloy composition, are also important factors to take into consideration.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Several theories have been elaborated to explain the depassivation process.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Anions with weak or strong ligand properties such as chloride (Cl− ) and thiosulfate (S 2O2− 3) respectively can complex the metallic cations (Men+) present in the protective oxide layer and so contribute to its local dissolution.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Chloride anions could also compete with hydroxide ions (OH− ) for the sorption onto the oxide layer and start to diffuse into the porosity or the crystal lattice of the oxide layer.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Finally, according to the point-defect model elaborated by Digby Macdonald, the migration of crystal defects inside the oxide layer could explain its random localized disappearance.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] The main interest of the point-defect model is to explain the stochastic character of the pitting corrosion process.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] The more common explanation for pitting corrosion is that it is an autocatalytic process driven by the random formation of small electrochemical cells with separate anodic and cathodic zones.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] The random local breakdown of the protective oxide layer and the subsequent oxidation of the underlying metal in the anodic zones result in the local formation of a pit where acid conditions are maintained by the spatial separation of the cathodic and anodic half-reactions.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] This creates a gradient of electrical potential and is responsible for the electromigration of aggressive anions into the pit.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] For example, when a metal is exposed to an oxygenated aqueous solution containing sodium chloride (NaCl) as electrolyte, the pit acts as anode (metal oxidation) and the metal surface acts as cathode (oxygen reduction).
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Acidic conditions favor the redox reaction according to Le Chatelier principle because the H+ ions added to the reagents side displace the reaction equilibrium to the right and also increase the solubility of the released Fe2+ cations.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] The precipitation of Fe(OH)2 (green rust) can also contribute to drive the reaction towards the right.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] However, the solubility of Fe(OH)2 (Fe2+) is relatively high (~ 100 times that of Fe3+), but strongly decreases when pH increases because of common ion effect with the OH−.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] In the two examples given here above: – Iron is a reductant giving electrons while being oxidized. – Oxygen is an oxidant taking up electrons while being reduced.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] The formation of anodic and cathodic zones creates an electrochemical cell (*i.e.*, a small electric battery) at the surface of the affected metal.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] The difference in Gibbs free energy (ΔG) drives the reaction because ΔG is negative and the system releases energy (enthalpy, ΔH < 0) while increasing entropy (ΔG = ΔH - TΔS).
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] The transport of dissolved ions occurs into the aqueous solution in contact with the corroding metal while electrons are transported from the anode (giving *e*−) to the cathode (accepting *e*−) via the base metal (electrical conductor).
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] The pit contains a high concentration of metal (Me) chloride (MeCln) which hydrolyzes with water to produce the corresponding metal hydroxide (Me(OH)n), and n H+ and n Cl– ions, accelerating the corrosion process.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] So, when chloride ions present in solution enter in contact with the steel surface, they react with Fe2+ of the passive layer protecting the steel surface and form an iron–chloride complex.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Then, the iron-chloride complex reacts with the OH− anions produced by the water dissociation and precipitates ferrous hydroxide (Fe(OH)2) while releasing chloride ions and new H+ ions available to continue the corrosion process.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] In the pit, the oxygen concentration is essentially zero and all of the cathodic oxygen reactions take place on the metal surface outside the pit.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] The pit is anodic (oxidation) and the locus of rapid dissolution of the metal.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] The metal corrosion initiation is autocatalytic in nature however its propagation is not.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] This kind of corrosion is often difficult to detect and so is extremely insidious, as it causes little loss of material with the small effect on its surface, while it damages the deep structures of the metal.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] The pits on the surface are often obscured by corrosion products.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Pitting can be initiated by a small surface defect, being a scratch or a local change in the alloy composition (or local impurities, *e.g.* metallic sulfide inclusions such as MnS or NiS), or a damage to the protective coating.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Polished surfaces display a higher resistance to pitting.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] In order to maintain the solution electroneutrality inside the pit populated by cations released by oxidation in the anodic zone (e.g., Fe2+ in case of steel), anions need to migrate inside the narrow pit.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] It is worth to notice that the electromobilities of thiosulfate (S 2O2− 3) and chloride (Cl− ) anions are the highest after these of H+ and OH− ions in aqueous solution.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Moreover, the molar conductivity of thiosulfate ions is even higher than that of chloride ions because they are twice negatively charged (weak base reluctant to accept a proton).
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] In capillary electrophoresis, thiosulfate moves faster than chloride and eluates before this latter.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] The high electromobility of both anions could also be one of the many factors explaining their harmful impact for pitting corrosion when compared with other much less damaging ion species such as SO2−4 and NO−3.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Pitting corrosion is defined by localized attack, ranging from microns to millimeters in diameter, in an otherwise passive surface and only occurs for specific alloy and environmental combinations.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Thus, this type of corrosion typically occurs in alloys that are protected by a tenacious (passivating) oxide film such as stainless steels, nickel alloys, aluminum alloys in environments that contain an aggressive species such as chlorides (Cl–) or thiosulfates (S2O32–).
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] In contrast, alloy/environment combinations where the passive film is not very protective usually will not produce pitting corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] A good example of the importance of alloy/environment combinations is carbon steel.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] In environments where the pH value is lower than 10, carbon steel does not form a passivating oxide film and the addition of chloride results in uniform attack over the entire surface.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] However, at pH greater than 10 (alkaline) the oxide is protective and the addition of chloride results in pitting corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Besides chlorides, other anions implicated in pitting include thiosulfates (S2O32−), fluorides and iodides.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Stagnant water conditions with low concentrations of dissolved oxygen also favor pitting.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Thiosulfates are particularly aggressive species and are formed by partial oxidation of pyrite (FeS2, a ferrous disulfide), or partial sulfate reduction by microorganisms, a.o. by sulfate reducing bacteria (SRB).
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Thiosulfates are a concern for corrosion in many industries handling sulfur-derived compounds: sulfide ores processing, oil wells and pipelines transporting soured oils, kraft paper production plants, photographic industry, methionine and lysine factories.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Although in the aforementioned example, oxic conditions were always considered with the reduction of dissolved O2 in the cathodic zones, pitting corrosion may also occur under anoxic, or reducing, conditions.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Indeed, the very harmful reduced species of sulfur (H2S, HS− , S2− , HS–S− , − S–S− , S0 and S 2O2− 3) can only subsist under reducing conditions.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Reductants exert thus an antagonist effect with respect to the oxidants (chromate, nitrite) used as corrosion inhibitors to induce steel repassivation via the formation of a dense γ-Fe 2O 3 protective layer.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Pitting corrosion can thus occur both under oxidizing and reducing conditions and can be aggravated in poorly oxygenated waters by differential aeration, or by drying/wetting cycles.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] The presence of harmful reduced species of sulfur and microbial activity feeding the sulfur cycle (sulfide oxidation possibly followed by bacterial sulfate reduction) have also to be taken into account.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Strictly abiotic (*i.e.* inorganic) corrosion processes are generally slower under anoxic conditions than under oxic conditions, but the presence of bacteria and biofilms can aggravate the degradation conditions and causes unexpected problems.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Different types of corrosion inhibitor exist.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Among them, oxidizing species such as chromate (CrO2− 4) and nitrite (NO− 2) were the first used to re-establish the state of passivation in the protective oxide layer.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] In the specific case of steel, the Fe2+ cation being a relatively soluble species, it contributes to favor the dissolution of the oxide layer which so loses its passivity.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] To restore the passivity, the principle simply consists to prevent the dissolution of the oxide layer by converting the soluble divalent Fe2+ cation into the much less soluble trivalent Fe3+ cation.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] This approach is also at the basis of the chromate conversion coating used to passivate steel, aluminium, zinc, cadmium, copper, silver, titanium, magnesium, and tin alloys.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] As hexavalent chromate is a known carcinogen, its aqueous effluents can no longer be freely discharged into the environment and its maximum concentration acceptable in water is very low.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Nitrite is also an oxidizing species and has been used as corrosion inhibitor since the 1950's.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Corrosion inhibitors, when present in sufficient amount, can provide protection against pitting.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] However, too low level of them can aggravate pitting by forming local anodes.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] A single pit in a critical point can cause a great deal of damage.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] One example is the explosion in Guadalajara, Mexico, on 22 April 1992, when gasoline fumes accumulated in sewers destroyed kilometers of streets.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] The vapors originated from a leak of gasoline through a single hole formed by corrosion between a steel gasoline pipe and a zinc-plated water pipe.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Firearms can also suffer from pitting, most notably in the bore of the barrel when corrosive ammunition is used and the barrel is not cleaned soon afterwards.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Deformities in the bore caused by pitting can greatly reduce the firearm's accuracy.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] To reduce pitting in firearm bores, most modern firearms have a bore lined with chromium.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Pitting corrosion can also help initiate stress corrosion cracking, as happened when a single eyebar on the Silver Bridge in West Virginia, United States, failed and killed 46 people on the bridge in December 1967.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] In laboratories, pitting corrosion may damage equipment, reducing its performance or longevity.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] Fume hoods are of particular concern, as the material constitution of their ductwork must suit the primary effluent(s) intended for exhaust.
[src:corrosion-science/pitting-corrosion] If the chosen vent material is unsuitable for the primary effluent(s), consequent pitting corrosion will prevent the fume hood from effectively containing harmful airborne particles.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Given sufficient time, any iron mass in the presence of water and oxygen will form rust and could eventually convert entirely to rust.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Surface rust is commonly flaky and friable, and provides no passivational protection to the underlying iron unlike other metals such as aluminum, copper, and tin which form stable oxide layers.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] *Rusting* is the common term for corrosion of elemental iron and its alloys such as steel.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Many other metals undergo similar corrosion, but the resulting oxides are not commonly called "rust".
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Several forms of rust are distinguishable both visually and by spectroscopy, and form under different circumstances.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Other forms of rust include the result of reactions between iron and chloride in an environment deprived of oxygen.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Rebar used in underwater concrete pillars, which generates green rust, is an example.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Although rusting is generally a negative aspect of iron, a particular form of rusting, known as *stable rust*, causes the object to have a thin coating of rust over the top; this results from reaction with atmospheric oxygen.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] If kept free of moisture, it makes the "stable" layer protective to the iron below, albeit not to the extent of other oxides such as aluminium oxide on aluminium.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Rust is a general name for a complex of oxides and hydroxides of iron, which occur when iron or some alloys that contain iron are exposed to oxygen and moisture for a long period of time.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Over time, the oxygen combines with the metal, forming new compounds collectively called rust, in a process called rusting.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Rusting is an oxidation reaction specifically occurring with iron.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Other metals also corrode via similar oxidation, but such corrosion is not called rusting.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] The main catalyst for the rusting process is water.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Iron or steel structures might appear to be solid, but water molecules can penetrate the microscopic pits and cracks in any exposed metal.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] The hydrogen atoms present in water molecules can combine with other elements to form acids, which will eventually cause more metal to be exposed.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] If chloride ions are present, as is the case with saltwater, the corrosion is likely to occur more quickly.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Meanwhile, the oxygen atoms combine with metallic atoms to form the destructive oxide compound.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] These iron compounds are brittle and crumbly and replace strong metallic iron, reducing the strength of the object.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] When iron is in contact with water and oxygen, it rusts.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] If salt is present, for example in seawater or salt spray, the iron tends to rust more quickly, as a result of chemical reactions.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Iron metal is relatively unaffected by pure water or by dry oxygen.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] As with other metals, like aluminium, a tightly adhering oxide coating, a passivation layer, protects the bulk iron from further oxidation.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] The conversion of the passivating ferrous oxide layer to rust results from the combined action of two agents, usually oxygen and water.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Other degrading solutions are sulfur dioxide in water and carbon dioxide in water.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Under these corrosive conditions, iron hydroxide species are formed.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Unlike ferrous oxides, the hydroxides do not adhere to the bulk metal.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] As they form and flake off from the surface, fresh iron is exposed, and the corrosion process continues until either all of the iron is consumed or all of the oxygen, water, carbon dioxide or sulfur dioxide in the system are removed or consumed.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] When iron rusts, the oxides take up more volume than the original metal; this expansion can generate enormous forces, damaging structures made with iron.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] The rusting of iron is an electrochemical process that begins with the transfer of electrons from iron to oxygen.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] The iron is the reducing agent (gives up electrons) while the oxygen is the oxidizing agent (gains electrons).
[src:corrosion-science/rust] The rate of corrosion is affected by water and accelerated by electrolytes, as illustrated by the effects of road salt on the corrosion of automobiles.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Because it forms hydroxide ions, this process is strongly affected by the presence of acid.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Likewise, the corrosion of most metals by oxygen is accelerated at low pH.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] From the above equations, it is also seen that the corrosion products are dictated by the availability of water and oxygen.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] With limited dissolved oxygen, iron(II)-containing materials are favoured, including FeO and black lodestone or magnetite (Fe3O4).
[src:corrosion-science/rust] High oxygen concentrations favour ferric materials with the nominal formulae Fe(OH)3−*x*O*x*⁄2.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] The nature of rust changes with time, reflecting the slow rates of the reactions of solids.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Furthermore, these complex processes are affected by the presence of other ions, such as Ca2+, which serve as electrolytes which accelerate rust formation, or combine with the hydroxides and oxides of iron to precipitate a variety of Ca, Fe, O, OH species.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] The onset of rusting can also be detected in the laboratory with the use of ferroxyl indicator solution.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] The solution detects both Fe2+ ions and hydroxyl ions.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Formation of Fe2+ ions and hydroxyl ions are indicated by blue and pink patches respectively.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Because of the widespread use and importance of iron and steel products, and because rusting severely compromises the strength, functionality and the appearance of such products, the prevention and control of rust is the basis of major economic activities in a number of specialized technologies.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] A brief overview of methods is presented here; for detailed coverage, see the cross-referenced articles.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Rust is permeable to air and water, therefore the interior metallic iron beneath a rust layer continues to corrode.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Rust prevention thus requires coatings that preclude rust formation.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Stainless steel forms a passivation layer of chromium(III) oxide.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Similar passivation behavior occurs with magnesium, titanium, zinc, zinc oxides, aluminium, polyaniline, and other electroactive conductive polymers.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Special "weathering steel" alloys such as Cor-Ten rust at a much slower rate than normal, because the rust adheres to the surface of the metal in a protective layer.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Designs using this material must include measures that avoid worst-case exposures since the material still continues to rust slowly even under near-ideal conditions.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Galvanization consists of an application on the object to be protected of a layer of metallic zinc by either hot-dip galvanizing or electroplating.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Zinc is traditionally used because it is cheap, adheres well to steel, and provides cathodic protection to the steel surface in case of damage of the zinc layer.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] In more corrosive environments (such as salt water), cadmium plating is preferred instead of the underlying protected metal.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] The protective zinc layer is consumed by this action, and thus galvanization provides protection only for a limited period of time.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] More modern coatings add aluminium to the coating as *zinc-alume*; aluminium will migrate to cover scratches and thus provide protection for a longer period.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] These approaches rely on the aluminium and zinc oxides protecting a once-scratched surface, rather than oxidizing as a sacrificial anode as in traditional galvanized coatings.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] In some cases, such as very aggressive environments or long design life, both zinc and a coating are applied to provide enhanced corrosion protection.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Typical galvanization of steel products that are to be subjected to normal day-to-day weathering in an outside environment consists of a hot-dipped 85 μm zinc coating.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Under normal weather conditions, this will deteriorate at a rate of 1 μm per year, giving approximately 85 years of protection.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Cathodic protection is a technique used to inhibit corrosion on buried or immersed structures by supplying an electrical charge that suppresses the electrochemical reaction.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] If correctly applied, corrosion can be stopped completely.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] In its simplest form, it is achieved by attaching a sacrificial anode, thereby making the iron or steel the cathode in the cell formed.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] The sacrificial anode must be made from something with a more negative electrode potential than the iron or steel, commonly zinc, aluminium, or magnesium.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] The sacrificial anode will eventually corrode away, ceasing its protective action unless it is replaced in a timely manner.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Cathodic protection can also be provided by using an applied electrical current.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] This would then be known as ICCP Impressed Current Cathodic Protection.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Rust formation can be controlled with coatings, such as paint, lacquer, varnish, or wax tapes that isolate the iron from the environment.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Large structures with enclosed box sections, such as ships and modern automobiles, often have a wax-based product (technically a "slushing oil") injected into these sections.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Such treatments usually also contain rust inhibitors.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Covering steel with concrete can provide some protection to steel because of the alkaline pH environment at the steel–concrete interface.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] However, rusting of steel in concrete can still be a problem, as expanding rust can fracture concrete from within.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] As a closely related example, iron clamps were used to join marble blocks during a restoration attempt of the Parthenon in Athens, Greece, in 1898, but caused extensive damage to the marble by the rusting and swelling of unprotected iron.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] The ancient Greek builders had used a similar fastening system for the marble blocks during construction, however, they also poured molten lead over the iron joints for protection from seismic shocks as well as from corrosion.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] This method was successful for the 2500-year-old structure, but in less than a century the crude repairs were in imminent danger of collapse.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] When only temporary protection is needed for storage or transport, a thin layer of oil, grease or a special mixture such as Cosmoline can be applied to an iron surface.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Such treatments are extensively used when "mothballing" a steel ship, automobile, or other equipment for long-term storage.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Special anti-seize lubricant mixtures are available and are applied to metallic threads and other precision machined surfaces to protect them from rust.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] These compounds usually contain grease mixed with copper, zinc, or aluminium powder, and other proprietary ingredients.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Bluing is a technique that can provide limited resistance to rusting for small steel items, such as firearms; for it to be successful, a water-displacing oil is rubbed onto the blued steel and other steel.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Corrosion inhibitors, such as gas-phase or volatile inhibitors, can be used to prevent corrosion inside sealed systems.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] They are not effective when air circulation disperses them, and brings in fresh oxygen and moisture.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Rust can be avoided by controlling the moisture in the atmosphere.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] An example of this is the use of silica gel packets to control humidity in equipment shipped by sea.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Hydrogen and oxygen gases are produced at the cathode and anode respectively.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Care should also be taken to avoid hydrogen embrittlement.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Overvoltage also produces small amounts of ozone, which is highly toxic, so a low voltage phone charger is a far safer source of DC current.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] The effects of hydrogen on global warming have also recently come under scrutiny.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Rust may be treated with commercial products known as rust converter which contain tannic acid or phosphoric acid which combines with rust; removed with organic acids like citric acid and vinegar or removed with chelating agents as in some commercial formulations or even a solution of molasses.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Rust is associated with the degradation of iron-based tools and structures.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] As rust has a much higher volume than the originating mass of iron, its buildup can also cause failure by forcing apart adjacent parts phenomenon sometimes known as "rust jacking".
[src:corrosion-science/rust] It was the cause of the collapse of the Mianus river bridge in 1983, when the bearings rusted internally and pushed one corner of the road slab off its support.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Silver Bridge disaster of 1967 in West Virginia, when a steel suspension bridge collapsed in less than a minute, killing 46 drivers and passengers on the bridge at the time.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] The Kinzua Bridge in Pennsylvania was blown down by a tornado in 2003, largely because the central base bolts holding the structure to the ground had rusted away, leaving the bridge anchored by gravity alone.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Reinforced concrete is also vulnerable to rust damage.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Internal pressure caused by expanding corrosion of concrete-covered steel and iron can cause the concrete to spall, creating severe structural problems.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] It is one of the most common failure modes of reinforced concrete bridges and buildings.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] Rust is a commonly used metaphor for slow decay due to neglect, since it gradually converts robust iron and steel metal into a soft crumbling powder.
[src:corrosion-science/rust] A wide section of the industrialized American Midwest and American Northeast, once dominated by steel foundries, the automotive industry, and other manufacturers, has experienced harsh economic cutbacks that have caused the region to be dubbed the "Rust Belt".
[src:corrosion-science/rust] In music, literature, and art, rust is associated with images of faded glory, neglect, entropy, decay, and ruin.
